<subSubSection lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="518" pageId="16" pageNumber="517" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,1807,2014]" lastBlockId="17.[151,1437,151,645]" lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="518" pageId="16" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="517">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. “Distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Girard" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[569,655,1951,1977]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cottidae" genus="Cottus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="16" pageNumber="517" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gulosus">
<emphasis box="[569,655,1951,1977]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="517">gulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by consistent absence of palatine teeth, the usually better-developed lateral line, and the typical complement of two preopercular spines (
<bibRefCitation author="Bailey, R. M. &amp; Bond, C. E." box="[900,1152,1987,2013]" pageId="16" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref14835" refString="Bailey, R. M. &amp; Bond, C. E. (1963) Four new species of freshwater sculpins, genus Cottus, from western North America. Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan, 634, 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="1963">Bailey and Bond 1963</bibRefCitation>
, p. 21). According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Bailey, R. M. &amp; Bond, C. E." lastPageId="17" lastPageNumber="518" pageId="16" pageNumber="517" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref14835" refString="Bailey, R. M. &amp; Bond, C. E. (1963) Four new species of freshwater sculpins, genus Cottus, from western North America. Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan, 634, 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="1963">Bailey and Bond (1963)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Girard" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[394,513,151,177]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cottidae" genus="Cottus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gulosus">
<emphasis box="[394,513,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">C. gulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 2–4 preopercular spines but usually 3, while 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Pit Sculpin Bailey and Bond" authorityYear="1963" box="[1062,1180,151,177]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cottidae" genus="Cottus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="pitensis">
<emphasis box="[1062,1180,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">C. pitensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has 1–3, but usually 2. In the original description, 
<bibRefCitation author="Girard, C." box="[451,605,186,213]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" pagination="129 - 165" refId="ref15987" refString="Girard, C. (1854) Descriptions of new fishes collected by Dr. A. L. Heermann, naturalist attached to the survey of the Pacific railroad route, under Lieut. R. S. Williamson, U. S. A. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia, 7, 129 - 165." type="journal article" year="1854">Girard (1854)</bibRefCitation>
noted that 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Girard" baseAuthorityYear="1854" box="[727,845,187,213]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Cottidae" genus="Cottus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpaeniformes" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gulosus">
<emphasis box="[727,845,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">C. gulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has two preopercular spines. All other characteristics show broad overlap (
<bibRefCitation author="Bailey, R. M. &amp; Bond, C. E." box="[385,639,223,250]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" pagination="1 - 27" refId="ref14835" refString="Bailey, R. M. &amp; Bond, C. E. (1963) Four new species of freshwater sculpins, genus Cottus, from western North America. Occasional Papers of the Museum of Zoology, University of Michigan, 634, 1 - 27." type="journal article" year="1963">Bailey and Bond 1963</bibRefCitation>
). Genomic studies (
<bibRefCitation author="Baumsteiger, J. &amp; Kinziger, A. P. &amp; Reid., S. B. &amp; Aguilar, A." box="[858,1129,223,249]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" pagination="2602 - 2618" refId="ref15005" refString="Baumsteiger, J., Kinziger, A. P., Reid., S. B. &amp; Aguilar, A. (2014) Complex phylogeography and historical hybridization between sister taxa of freshwater sculpin (Cottus). Molecular Ecology, 23, 2602 - 2618. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / mec. 12758" type="journal article" year="2014">
Baumsteiger 
<emphasis box="[1008,1056,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">et al</emphasis>
. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
, this study) confirm its species status, as does the distinct distribution. See 
<tableCitation box="[689,772,259,285]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="4.[150,238,542,568]" captionTargetBox="[165,1966,655,1605]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="TABLE 1. Meristic values for Riffle Sculpin samples from the UC Davis Museum of Wildlife and Fish and the California Academy of Sciences, San Francisco. Cottus asper and C.pitensis data is presented for comparison.? means ‘could not be determined’. Locations include the year collected. See Table 2 for more precise location information. Sculpins at locations with * were C. asper originally identified as C. gulosus" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Table 1</tableCitation>
for meristic counts on specimens used in this study (n=8).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="518" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,339,294,321]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Distribution</emphasis>
. Endemic to the Pit River watershed in northeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[969,1083,295,321]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">California</collectingRegion>
and southeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[1296,1384,295,321]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Oregon</collectingRegion>
. 
<collectingRegion country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Oregon</collectingRegion>
populations are found in tributaries to Goose Lake, including Drews, Cottonwood, and Thomas creeks (Lake County, 
<collectingRegion box="[247,336,367,393]" country="United States of America" name="Oregon" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Oregon</collectingRegion>
). In 
<collectingRegion box="[387,503,367,393]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">California</collectingRegion>
, the Pit Sculpin is found in tributaries to Goose Lake (Lassen and Willow Creeks) and then south in streams throughout the Pit River watershed (Modoc and Shasta counties) to Squaw Valley Creek, now a tributary to Shasta Reservoir. 
<bibRefCitation author="Kinziger, A. P. &amp; Hellmair, M. &amp; Fong, S. R. &amp; Goodman, D. H. &amp; Kelsey, H." box="[560,804,439,466]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518" pagination="1257 - 1267" refId="ref16352" refString="Kinziger, A. P., Hellmair, M., Fong, S. R., Goodman, D. H. &amp; Kelsey, H. (2016) Evolution of rough sculpin (Cottus asperrimus): genetic divergence and late Quaternary displacement on the Hat Creek fault, California, USA. Conservation Genetics, 17 (6), 1257 - 1267. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 10592 - 016 - 0859 - 9" type="journal article" year="2016">
Kinziger 
<emphasis box="[665,715,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">et al</emphasis>
. (2016)
</bibRefCitation>
note that the complex geologic history of the region has resulted in some population structure in the Pit Sculpin, suggesting further investigation of its taxonomic relationships is needed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="518" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[151,1437,151,645]" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,546,573]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="518">Etymology</emphasis>
. Named after the Pit River, which encompasses its distribution. The Pit River was so named because early Euro-American visitors were impressed by the deep pits dug by the native peoples to trap wildlife (
<bibRefCitation author="Gudde, E. G. &amp; Bright, W." pageId="17" pageNumber="518" refId="ref16050" refString="Gudde, E. G. &amp; Bright, W. (1998) California Place Names. University of California Press, Berkeley, 172 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1525 / 9780520920545" type="book" year="1998">Gudde and Bright 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
